{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"I'm going to talk today"},{"time":2000,"text":"about the pleasures of everyday life."},{"time":4000,"text":"But I want to begin with a story"},{"time":6000,"text":"of an unusual and terrible man."},{"time":8000,"text":"This is Hermann Goering."},{"time":10000,"text":"Goering was Hitler's second in command in World War II,"},{"time":13000,"text":"his designated successor."},{"time":15000,"text":"And like Hitler,"},{"time":17000,"text":"Goering fancied himself a collector of art."},{"time":19000,"text":"He went through Europe, through World War II,"},{"time":21000,"text":"stealing, extorting and occasionally buying"},{"time":24000,"text":"various paintings for his collection."},{"time":26000,"text":"And what he really wanted was something by Vermeer."},{"time":29000,"text":"Hitler had two of them, and he didn't have any."},{"time":32000,"text":"So he finally found an art dealer,"},{"time":34000,"text":"a Dutch art dealer named Han van Meegeren,"},{"time":37000,"text":"who sold him a wonderful Vermeer"},{"time":39000,"text":"for the cost of what would now be 10 million dollars."},{"time":42000,"text":"And it was his favorite artwork ever."}]},{"cues":[{"time":45000,"text":"World War II came to an end,"},{"time":47000,"text":"and Goering was captured, tried at Nuremberg"},{"time":50000,"text":"and ultimately sentenced to death."},{"time":53000,"text":"Then the Allied forces went through his collections"},{"time":55000,"text":"and found the paintings"},{"time":57000,"text":"and went after the people who sold it to him."},{"time":59000,"text":"And at some point the Dutch police came into Amsterdam"},{"time":62000,"text":"and arrested Van Meegeren."},{"time":64000,"text":"Van Meegeren was charged with the crime of treason,"},{"time":67000,"text":"which is itself punishable by death."},{"time":70000,"text":"Six weeks into his prison sentence,"},{"time":72000,"text":"van Meegeren confessed."},{"time":74000,"text":"But he didn't confess to treason."},{"time":76000,"text":"He said, \"I did not sell a great masterpiece"},{"time":79000,"text":"to that Nazi."},{"time":81000,"text":"I painted it myself; I'm a forger.\""},{"time":84000,"text":"Now nobody believed him."},{"time":87000,"text":"And he said, \"I'll prove it."},{"time":89000,"text":"Bring me a canvas and some paint,"},{"time":91000,"text":"and I will paint a Vermeer much better"},{"time":93000,"text":"than I sold that disgusting Nazi."},{"time":95000,"text":"I also need alcohol and morphine, because it's the only way I can work.\""},{"time":98000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":100000,"text":"So they brought him in."},{"time":102000,"text":"He painted a beautiful Vermeer."},{"time":105000,"text":"And then the charges of treason were dropped."},{"time":108000,"text":"He had a lesser charge of forgery,"},{"time":110000,"text":"got a year sentence"},{"time":112000,"text":"and died a hero to the Dutch people."},{"time":116000,"text":"There's a lot more to be said about van Meegeren,"},{"time":119000,"text":"but I want to turn now to Goering,"},{"time":121000,"text":"who's pictured here being interrogated at Nuremberg."}]},{"cues":[{"time":124000,"text":"Now Goering was, by all accounts, a terrible man."},{"time":126000,"text":"Even for a Nazi, he was a terrible man."},{"time":129000,"text":"His American interrogators described him"},{"time":132000,"text":"as an amicable psychopath."},{"time":134000,"text":"But you could feel sympathy"},{"time":136000,"text":"for the reaction he had"},{"time":138000,"text":"when he was told that his favorite painting"},{"time":140000,"text":"was actually a forgery."},{"time":142000,"text":"According to his biographer,"},{"time":144000,"text":"\"He looked as if for the first time"},{"time":146000,"text":"he had discovered there was evil in the world.\""},{"time":148000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":151000,"text":"And he killed himself soon afterwards."},{"time":154000,"text":"He had discovered after all"},{"time":156000,"text":"that the painting he thought was this"},{"time":158000,"text":"was actually that."},{"time":161000,"text":"It looked the same,"},{"time":163000,"text":"but it had a different origin, it was a different artwork."}]},{"cues":[{"time":165000,"text":"It wasn't just him who was in for a shock."},{"time":167000,"text":"Once van Meegeren was on trial, he couldn't stop talking."},{"time":170000,"text":"And he boasted about all the great masterpieces"},{"time":172000,"text":"that he himself had painted"},{"time":174000,"text":"that were attributed to other artists."},{"time":176000,"text":"In particular, \"The Supper at Emmaus\""},{"time":178000,"text":"which was viewed as Vermeer's finest masterpiece, his best work --"},{"time":181000,"text":"people would come [from] all over the world to see it --"},{"time":184000,"text":"was actually a forgery."},{"time":186000,"text":"It was not that painting, but that painting."},{"time":188000,"text":"And when that was discovered,"},{"time":190000,"text":"it lost all its value and was taken away from the museum."}]},{"cues":[{"time":193000,"text":"Why does this matter?"},{"time":195000,"text":"I'm a psychologists -- why do origins matter so much?"},{"time":198000,"text":"Why do we respond so much"},{"time":200000,"text":"to our knowledge of where something comes from?"},{"time":203000,"text":"Well there's an answer that many people would give."},{"time":205000,"text":"Many sociologists like Veblen and Wolfe"},{"time":208000,"text":"would argue that the reason why we take origins so seriously"},{"time":211000,"text":"is because we're snobs, because we're focused on status."},{"time":214000,"text":"Among other things,"},{"time":216000,"text":"if you want to show off how rich you are, how powerful you are,"},{"time":218000,"text":"it's always better to own an original than a forgery"},{"time":220000,"text":"because there's always going to be fewer originals than forgeries."},{"time":224000,"text":"I don't doubt that that plays some role,"},{"time":226000,"text":"but what I want to convince you of today"},{"time":228000,"text":"is that there's something else going on."},{"time":230000,"text":"I want to convince you"},{"time":232000,"text":"that humans are, to some extent, natural born essentialists."},{"time":235000,"text":"What I mean by this"},{"time":237000,"text":"is we don't just respond to things as we see them,"},{"time":239000,"text":"or feel them, or hear them."},{"time":241000,"text":"Rather, our response is conditioned on our beliefs,"},{"time":244000,"text":"about what they really are, what they came from,"},{"time":247000,"text":"what they're made of, what their hidden nature is."},{"time":250000,"text":"I want to suggest that this is true,"},{"time":252000,"text":"not just for how we think about things,"},{"time":254000,"text":"but how we react to things."}]},{"cues":[{"time":256000,"text":"So I want to suggest that pleasure is deep --"},{"time":258000,"text":"and that this isn't true"},{"time":260000,"text":"just for higher level pleasures like art,"},{"time":263000,"text":"but even the most seemingly simple pleasures"},{"time":266000,"text":"are affected by our beliefs about hidden essences."},{"time":269000,"text":"So take food."},{"time":271000,"text":"Would you eat this?"},{"time":273000,"text":"Well, a good answer is, \"It depends. What is it?\""},{"time":276000,"text":"Some of you would eat it if it's pork, but not beef."},{"time":278000,"text":"Some of you would eat it if it's beef, but not pork."},{"time":281000,"text":"Few of you would eat it if it's a rat"},{"time":283000,"text":"or a human."},{"time":285000,"text":"Some of you would eat it only if it's a strangely colored piece of tofu."},{"time":289000,"text":"That's not so surprising."}]},{"cues":[{"time":291000,"text":"But what's more interesting"},{"time":293000,"text":"is how it tastes to you"},{"time":295000,"text":"will depend critically on what you think you're eating."},{"time":298000,"text":"So one demonstration of this was done with young children."},{"time":301000,"text":"How do you make children"},{"time":303000,"text":"not just be more likely to eat carrots and drink milk,"},{"time":306000,"text":"but to get more pleasure from eating carrots and drinking milk --"},{"time":309000,"text":"to think they taste better?"},{"time":311000,"text":"It's simple, you tell them they're from McDonald's."},{"time":314000,"text":"They believe McDonald's food is tastier,"},{"time":316000,"text":"and it leads them to experience it as tastier."}]},{"cues":[{"time":319000,"text":"How do you get adults to really enjoy wine?"},{"time":321000,"text":"It's very simple:"},{"time":323000,"text":"pour it from an expensive bottle."},{"time":325000,"text":"There are now dozens, perhaps hundreds of studies showing"},{"time":328000,"text":"that if you believe you're drinking the expensive stuff,"},{"time":330000,"text":"it tastes better to you."},{"time":332000,"text":"This was recently done with a neuroscientific twist."},{"time":335000,"text":"They get people into a fMRI scanner,"},{"time":337000,"text":"and while they're lying there, through a tube,"},{"time":339000,"text":"they get to sip wine."},{"time":341000,"text":"In front of them on a screen is information about the wine."},{"time":344000,"text":"Everybody, of course,"},{"time":346000,"text":"drinks exactly the same wine."},{"time":348000,"text":"But if you believe you're drinking expensive stuff,"},{"time":351000,"text":"parts of the brain associated with pleasure and reward"},{"time":354000,"text":"light up like a Christmas tree."},{"time":356000,"text":"It's not just that you say it's more pleasurable, you say you like it more,"},{"time":359000,"text":"you really experience it in a different way."}]},{"cues":[{"time":362000,"text":"Or take sex."},{"time":365000,"text":"These are stimuli I've used in some of my studies."},{"time":368000,"text":"And if you simply show people these pictures,"},{"time":371000,"text":"they'll say these are fairly attractive people."},{"time":373000,"text":"But how attractive you find them,"},{"time":376000,"text":"how sexually or romantically moved you are by them,"},{"time":379000,"text":"rests critically on who you think you're looking at."},{"time":382000,"text":"You probably think the picture on the left is male,"},{"time":385000,"text":"the one on the right is female."},{"time":387000,"text":"If that belief turns out to be mistaken, it will make a difference."},{"time":390000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":392000,"text":"It will make a difference if they turn out to be"},{"time":394000,"text":"much younger or much older than you think they are."},{"time":397000,"text":"It will make a difference if you were to discover"},{"time":399000,"text":"that the person you're looking at with lust"},{"time":401000,"text":"is actually a disguised version of your son or daughter,"},{"time":403000,"text":"your mother or father."},{"time":405000,"text":"Knowing somebody's your kin typically kills the libido."},{"time":408000,"text":"Maybe one of the most heartening findings"},{"time":410000,"text":"from the psychology of pleasure"},{"time":412000,"text":"is there's more to looking good than your physical appearance."},{"time":415000,"text":"If you like somebody, they look better to you."},{"time":418000,"text":"This is why spouses in happy marriages"},{"time":421000,"text":"tend to think that their husband or wife"},{"time":423000,"text":"looks much better than anyone else thinks that they do."}]},{"cues":[{"time":426000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":428000,"text":"A particularly dramatic example of this"},{"time":431000,"text":"comes from a neurological disorder known as Capgras syndrome."},{"time":434000,"text":"So Capgras syndrome is a disorder"},{"time":437000,"text":"where you get a specific delusion."},{"time":439000,"text":"Sufferers of Capgras syndrome"},{"time":441000,"text":"believe that the people they love most in the world"},{"time":443000,"text":"have been replaced by perfect duplicates."},{"time":445000,"text":"Now often, a result of Capgras syndrome is tragic."},{"time":448000,"text":"People have murdered those that they loved,"},{"time":450000,"text":"believing that they were murdering an imposter."},{"time":453000,"text":"But there's at least one case"},{"time":455000,"text":"where Capgras syndrome had a happy ending."},{"time":457000,"text":"This was recorded in 1931."},{"time":459000,"text":"\"Research described a woman with Capgras syndrome"},{"time":462000,"text":"who complained about her poorly endowed and sexually inadequate lover.\""},{"time":465000,"text":"But that was before she got Capgras syndrome."},{"time":468000,"text":"After she got it, \"She was happy to report"},{"time":470000,"text":"that she has discovered that he possessed a double"},{"time":473000,"text":"who was rich, virile, handsome and aristocratic.\""},{"time":475000,"text":"Of course, it was the same man,"},{"time":477000,"text":"but she was seeing him in different ways."}]},{"cues":[{"time":479000,"text":"As a third example,"},{"time":481000,"text":"consider consumer products."},{"time":483000,"text":"So one reason why you might like something is its utility."},{"time":486000,"text":"You can put shoes on your feet; you can play golf with golf clubs;"},{"time":489000,"text":"and chewed up bubble gum doesn't do anything at all for you."},{"time":492000,"text":"But each of these three objects has value"},{"time":494000,"text":"above and beyond what it can do for you"},{"time":496000,"text":"based on its history."},{"time":498000,"text":"The golf clubs were owned by John F. Kennedy"},{"time":501000,"text":"and sold for three-quarters of a million dollars at auction."},{"time":504000,"text":"The bubble gum was chewed up by pop star Britney Spears"},{"time":507000,"text":"and sold for several hundreds of dollars."},{"time":509000,"text":"And in fact, there's a thriving market"},{"time":511000,"text":"in the partially eaten food of beloved people."},{"time":514000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":516000,"text":"The shoes are perhaps the most valuable of all."},{"time":519000,"text":"According to an unconfirmed report,"},{"time":521000,"text":"a Saudi millionaire offered 10 million dollars"},{"time":523000,"text":"for this pair of shoes."},{"time":525000,"text":"They were the ones thrown at George Bush"},{"time":528000,"text":"at an Iraqi press conference several years ago."}]},{"cues":[{"time":530000,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":532000,"text":"Now this attraction to objects"},{"time":534000,"text":"doesn't just work for celebrity objects."},{"time":536000,"text":"Each one of us, most people,"},{"time":538000,"text":"have something in our life that's literally irreplaceable,"},{"time":541000,"text":"in that it has value because of its history --"},{"time":544000,"text":"maybe your wedding ring, maybe your child's baby shoes --"},{"time":547000,"text":"so that if it was lost, you couldn't get it back."},{"time":550000,"text":"You could get something that looked like it or felt like it,"},{"time":552000,"text":"but you couldn't get the same object back."},{"time":555000,"text":"With my colleagues George Newman and Gil Diesendruck,"},{"time":558000,"text":"we've looked to see what sort of factors, what sort of history, matters"},{"time":561000,"text":"for the objects that people like."},{"time":563000,"text":"So in one of our experiments,"},{"time":565000,"text":"we asked people to name a famous person who they adored,"},{"time":568000,"text":"a living person they adored."}]},{"cues":[{"time":570000,"text":"So one answer was George Clooney."},{"time":572000,"text":"Then we asked them,"},{"time":574000,"text":"\"How much would you pay for George Clooney's sweater?\""},{"time":576000,"text":"And the answer is a fair amount --"},{"time":578000,"text":"more than you would pay for a brand new sweater"},{"time":581000,"text":"or a sweater owned by somebody who you didn't adore."},{"time":584000,"text":"Then we asked other groups of subjects --"},{"time":586000,"text":"we gave them different restrictions"},{"time":588000,"text":"and different conditions."},{"time":590000,"text":"So for instance, we told some people,"},{"time":592000,"text":"\"Look, you can buy the sweater,"},{"time":594000,"text":"but you can't tell anybody you own it,"},{"time":596000,"text":"and you can't resell it.\""},{"time":598000,"text":"That drops the value of it,"},{"time":600000,"text":"suggesting that that's one reason why we like it."},{"time":603000,"text":"But what really causes an effect"},{"time":605000,"text":"is you tell people, \"Look, you could resell it, you could boast about it,"},{"time":608000,"text":"but before it gets to you,"},{"time":610000,"text":"it's thoroughly washed.\""},{"time":612000,"text":"That causes a huge drop in the value."},{"time":615000,"text":"As my wife put it, \"You've washed away the Clooney cooties.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":618000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":620000,"text":"So let's go back to art."},{"time":622000,"text":"I would love a Chagall. I love the work of Chagall."},{"time":624000,"text":"If people want to get me something at the end of the conference,"},{"time":626000,"text":"you could buy me a Chagall."},{"time":628000,"text":"But I don't want a duplicate,"},{"time":630000,"text":"even if I can't tell the difference."},{"time":632000,"text":"That's not because, or it's not simply because,"},{"time":634000,"text":"I'm a snob and want to boast about having an original."},{"time":637000,"text":"Rather, it's because I want something that has a specific history."},{"time":640000,"text":"In the case of artwork,"},{"time":642000,"text":"the history is special indeed."},{"time":644000,"text":"The philosopher Denis Dutton"},{"time":646000,"text":"in his wonderful book \"The Art Instinct\""},{"time":648000,"text":"makes the case that, \"The value of an artwork"},{"time":650000,"text":"is rooted in assumptions about the human performance underlying its creation.\""},{"time":653000,"text":"And that could explain the difference"},{"time":655000,"text":"between an original and a forgery."},{"time":657000,"text":"They may look alike, but they have a different history."},{"time":659000,"text":"The original is typically the product of a creative act,"},{"time":662000,"text":"the forgery isn't."},{"time":664000,"text":"I think this approach can explain differences"},{"time":667000,"text":"in people's taste in art."}]},{"cues":[{"time":669000,"text":"This is a work by Jackson Pollock."},{"time":671000,"text":"Who here likes the work of Jackson Pollock?"},{"time":675000,"text":"Okay. Who here, it does nothing for them?"},{"time":677000,"text":"They just don't like it."},{"time":680000,"text":"I'm not going to make a claim about who's right,"},{"time":682000,"text":"but I will make an empirical claim"},{"time":684000,"text":"about people's intuitions,"},{"time":686000,"text":"which is that, if you like the work of Jackson Pollock,"},{"time":688000,"text":"you'll tend more so than the people who don't like it"},{"time":691000,"text":"to believe that these works are difficult to create,"},{"time":694000,"text":"that they require a lot of time and energy"},{"time":696000,"text":"and creative energy."},{"time":698000,"text":"I use Jackson Pollock on purpose as an example"},{"time":701000,"text":"because there's a young American artist"},{"time":703000,"text":"who paints very much in the style of Jackson Pollock,"},{"time":705000,"text":"and her work was worth"},{"time":707000,"text":"many tens of thousands of dollars --"},{"time":709000,"text":"in large part because she's a very young artist."}]},{"cues":[{"time":711000,"text":"This is Marla Olmstead"},{"time":713000,"text":"who did most of her work when she was three years old."},{"time":715000,"text":"The interesting thing about Marla Olmstead"},{"time":717000,"text":"is her family made the mistake"},{"time":719000,"text":"of inviting the television program 60 Minutes II into their house"},{"time":723000,"text":"to film her painting."},{"time":725000,"text":"And they then reported that her father was coaching her."},{"time":728000,"text":"When this came out on television,"},{"time":730000,"text":"the value of her art dropped to nothing."},{"time":733000,"text":"It was the same art, physically,"},{"time":735000,"text":"but the history had changed."}]},{"cues":[{"time":738000,"text":"I've been focusing now on the visual arts,"},{"time":740000,"text":"but I want to give two examples from music."},{"time":742000,"text":"This is Joshua Bell, a very famous violinist."},{"time":744000,"text":"And the Washington Post reporter Gene Weingarten"},{"time":747000,"text":"decided to enlist him for an audacious experiment."},{"time":750000,"text":"The question is: How much would people like Joshua Bell,"},{"time":752000,"text":"the music of Joshua Bell,"},{"time":754000,"text":"if they didn't know they were listening to Joshua Bell?"},{"time":758000,"text":"So he got Joshua Bell to take his million dollar violin"},{"time":761000,"text":"down to a Washington D.C. subway station"},{"time":764000,"text":"and stand in the corner and see how much money he would make."},{"time":767000,"text":"And here's a brief clip of this."},{"time":769000,"text":"(Violin music)"},{"time":776000,"text":"After being there for three-quarters of an hour,"},{"time":778000,"text":"he made 32 dollars."},{"time":781000,"text":"Not bad. It's also not good."},{"time":783000,"text":"Apparently to really enjoy the music of Joshua Bell,"},{"time":786000,"text":"you have to know you're listening to Joshua Bell."},{"time":789000,"text":"He actually made 20 dollars more than that,"},{"time":791000,"text":"but he didn't count it."},{"time":793000,"text":"Because this woman comes up --"},{"time":795000,"text":"you see at the end of the video -- she comes up."},{"time":797000,"text":"She had heard him at the Library of Congress a few weeks before"},{"time":799000,"text":"at this extravagant black-tie affair."},{"time":802000,"text":"So she's stunned that he's standing in a subway station."},{"time":805000,"text":"So she's struck with pity."},{"time":807000,"text":"She reaches into her purse and hands him a 20."}]},{"cues":[{"time":809000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":811000,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":813000,"text":"The second example from music"},{"time":815000,"text":"is from John Cage's modernist composition,"},{"time":817000,"text":"\"4'33\".\""},{"time":819000,"text":"As many of you know,"},{"time":821000,"text":"this is the composition where the pianist sits at a bench,"},{"time":824000,"text":"opens up the piano"},{"time":826000,"text":"and sits and does nothing for four minutes and 33 seconds --"},{"time":828000,"text":"that period of silence."},{"time":830000,"text":"And people have different views on this."},{"time":832000,"text":"But what I want to point out"},{"time":834000,"text":"is you can buy this from iTunes."},{"time":836000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":838000,"text":"For a dollar 99,"},{"time":840000,"text":"you can listen to that silence,"},{"time":842000,"text":"which is different than other forms of silence."}]},{"cues":[{"time":845000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":847000,"text":"Now I've been talking so far about pleasure,"},{"time":850000,"text":"but what I want to suggest"},{"time":852000,"text":"is that everything I've said applies as well to pain."},{"time":855000,"text":"And how you think about what you're experiencing,"},{"time":857000,"text":"your beliefs about the essence of it,"},{"time":859000,"text":"affect how it hurts."},{"time":861000,"text":"One lovely experiment"},{"time":863000,"text":"was done by Kurt Gray and Dan Wegner."},{"time":865000,"text":"What they did was they hooked up Harvard undergraduates"},{"time":867000,"text":"to an electric shock machine."},{"time":869000,"text":"And they gave them a series of painful electric shocks."},{"time":872000,"text":"So it was a series of five painful shocks."},{"time":875000,"text":"Half of them are told that they're being given the shocks"},{"time":877000,"text":"by somebody in another room,"},{"time":879000,"text":"but the person in the other room doesn't know they're giving them shocks."},{"time":882000,"text":"There's no malevolence, they're just pressing a button."},{"time":884000,"text":"The first shock is recorded as very painful."},{"time":887000,"text":"The second shock feels less painful, because you get a bit used to it."},{"time":890000,"text":"The third drops, the fourth, the fifth."},{"time":892000,"text":"The pain gets less."},{"time":895000,"text":"In the other condition,"},{"time":897000,"text":"they're told that the person in the next room"},{"time":899000,"text":"is shocking them on purpose -- knows they're shocking them."},{"time":902000,"text":"The first shock hurts like hell."},{"time":904000,"text":"The second shock hurts just as much,"},{"time":906000,"text":"and the third and the fourth and the fifth."},{"time":908000,"text":"It hurts more"},{"time":910000,"text":"if you believe somebody is doing it to you on purpose."}]},{"cues":[{"time":913000,"text":"The most extreme example of this"},{"time":916000,"text":"is that in some cases,"},{"time":918000,"text":"pain under the right circumstances"},{"time":920000,"text":"can transform into pleasure."},{"time":922000,"text":"Humans have this extraordinarily interesting property"},{"time":925000,"text":"that will often seek out low-level doses of pain"},{"time":927000,"text":"in controlled circumstances"},{"time":929000,"text":"and take pleasure from it --"},{"time":931000,"text":"as in the eating of hot chili peppers"},{"time":933000,"text":"and roller coaster rides."},{"time":936000,"text":"The point was nicely summarized"},{"time":938000,"text":"by the poet John Milton"},{"time":940000,"text":"who wrote, \"The mind is its own place,"},{"time":942000,"text":"and in itself can make a heaven of hell,"},{"time":944000,"text":"a hell of heaven.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":946000,"text":"And I'll end with that. Thank you."}]},{"cues":[{"time":948000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}